SOME NOTIONS on a MESH of a LINE:
=================================

The mesh of a LINE is a set of EDGES, 
stored in 2 TMS a___xyzsommet and a___nsef,
defined by:

- NBSOM 3D vertices of coordinates (Xi,Yi,Zi) in a___xyzsommet TMS
- the array of (number vertex1, number vertex2) for the NBEFOB EDGES

        V1*................*V2
      A straigth edge (P1 interpolation)

Eventually,
- NBTGS 3D tangents of components (TXi,TYi,TZi) in a___xyzsommet TMS
- the array of (number tangent1, number tangent2)
at the 2 vertices of the NBEFTG EDGES or CURVED EDGES in a___nsef TMS

This storage permits a parametrization of the edge by polynameials
of degree 3 (Hermite interpolation)

             ^                  ^
            /                    \
           /                      \
      TG1 /      .   .    .        \TG2
         /   .                 .    \
        / .                        . \
       /.                            .\
    V1*                                *V2
        A curved edge (P3 interpolation)

In fact, if the line is simply connex and opened, it is sufficient
to store the number NBSOM=NBEFOB+1 of vertices and use an implicit 
numbering (i,i+1) for the 2 vertices (and 2 tangents) of the edge i.
In this case, the mesh is said STRUCTURED, else, it is said UNSTRUCTURED


A number of edges of the LINE is often demanded.
Estimate the length of edges before to give this value.
The heterogeneity of edge lengths can not produce good FE qualities
A large and a small edge at a same vertex
can not produce regular triangles or tetrahedra...

A geometrical ratio on the edge lengths is demanded
Give the geometrical ratio RATIO of the lengths Li of edges:
To have a list of values Li  with Li+1 / Li = RATIO
- constant   choose RATIO=1
- ascending  choose RATIO>1
- descending choose RATIO<1
It is reasonable to choose RATIO value in the vicinity of 1.0!
A 0<ratio<1 => small edges at the superior part
A   ratio>1 => small edges at the inferior part

Attention:
These 2 values, edge number and geometrical ratio becomes INEFFICIENT
if a User's function TAILLE_IDEALE(x,y,z) HAS BEEN GIVEN!
In this case, these 2 values are not used, but MUST BE GIVEN! Sorry.
The mesh algorithms compute the edges to satisfy the
edge length, result of the call of TAILLE_IDEALE(x,y,z) and
this is not compatible to a fixed number of edges!

Attention:
For STRUCTURED MESHES as STRUCTURED TRIANGLE or
STRUCTURED QUADRANGLE, the call of TAILLE_IDEALE(x,y,z) is not
done because the mesh algorithm is not compatible with!

Example for the input of Taille_Ideale:
DefVar lxf,lh2,lh3;
lh2=0.3;
lh3=0.7;
lxf=max(lh2,lh3);

DefFunc Taille_Ideale(x,y,z);
  Taille_Ideale=0.45;
  If x<lxf and y>-(lh3+lh2)*1.2
    Then Taille_Ideale=0.15;
  Else
    If x<lxf and y>-(lh3+lh2)*1.8
    Then Taille_Ideale=0.28;
    EndIf;
  EndIf;
EndFunc;


A LINE MAY BE CONSTRUCTED BY THE FOLLOWING OPTIONS:

2 : STRAIGHT LINE
    Example: LINE2; I; 2; 25; 1; P1; P2;
    define a straigth line from P1 to P2 with
    25 edges of same length

3 : ARC OF CIRCLE PASSING BY 3 3D-POINTS
    Example: LINE3; I; 3; 35; 1.1; P1; P2; P3;
    define 35 edges of vertices on the arc of circle
    of extremities P1 P2, passing by P3 (between P1 and P2)
    The edge lengths have a ratio of 1.1.
    Thus, the nearest edges from P1 are smaller than
    the nearest edges of P2.

4 : ARC OF CIRCLE PASSING BY 2+1 POINTS+RADIUS
    Example: LINE4; I; 4; 35; 1.1; P1; P2; P3; 1.5;
    define 35 edges of vertices on the arc of circle P1-P2
    de radius 1.5 in the plane P1 P2 P3.
    As 2 circles are possibles, the centre of chosen circle
   is the nearest of the P3 point

5 : ARC OF ELLIPSE OF R2 BY CENTRE AND XY AXES
    Example: LINE5; I; 5; 22; CENTR; 5; 3; P1; P2; -1;
    define 22 edges on the arc of ellipse from P2 to P1
    ellipse of centre the point CENTR and with main axes
    X of major radius 5 an Y of minor radius 3.

6 : LIST OF POINTS NAMED BY YOU
    Example: LINE6; I; 1; 5; P1;P2;P3;P4;P5;
    define a line of 4 edges P1-P2, P2-P3, P3-P4, P4-P5
    Only ONE edge between 2 successive points

7 : LIST OF VERTICES DEFINED BY THEIRS X Y Z
    Example: LINE7; I; 3;  0; 0; 0;  1; 0; 0;  1; 1; 0;
    define a line of 2 edges defined by 3 vertices  
    Only ONE edge between 2 successive vertices

8 : COMPLETE 3D CIRCLE
    Example: LINE8.1; I; 8; 24; 1; P1;P2;P3;
    define 24 edges of constant length, of vertices on
    the circle passing by P1 P2 and P3. 
    Example: LINE8.2; I; 8; 28; 2;
             CENTRE; PT_ON_CIRCLE; P_PLANE;
    define a closed line unstructured of 28 edges of constant length
    of vertices on the circle defined by the point CENTRE,
    passing by PT_ON_CIRCLE and in the PLANE defined
    by the 3 points CENTRE  PT_ON_CIRCLE  P_PLANE

9 : COMPLETE 2D ELLIPSE
    Example: LINE9; I; 9; 23; CENTRE; 5; 3;
    define 23 edges on the ellipse of centre the point CENTR and
    main axes X of major radius 5 et Y minus radius 3.

10: DATA OF ARRAYS XYZSOMMET ET NSEF
    These 2 arrays will be initialized value by value:
    . the first array contains the number and 
      the 3 coordinates of edge vertices
    . the second array contains the vertex number of 2 extremities 
      of every edge
    Example: LINE10; I; 10;
             3;0;3;   0;0;0; 1;0;0;  0.5;sqrt(3)/2;0; {3 vertices}
             2; 1; 2; 0; {line closed 2vertices/edge 0tg}
             3; 0; 0; 0; {3edges line 0tg unstructured}
             1;2; 2;3; 3;1; {number of 2 vertices of 3 edges}
    define a line composed of 3 edges of length 1,
    contour of a regular triangle

11: OPENED B-SPLINE FROM INTERPOLATION POINTS
    a B-spline is a parameterized curve by piecewise polynomials
    It is  possible to define
    the degree of polynomials
    the number and the name of interpolation points
    the number of edges on this curve
    the length of edges may follow a geometrical ratio
    ATTENTION: the number of interpolation points must be
               > degree of polynomials
               the curve degree-1 differential continuous
    Example: LINE11; I; 11;
             50; 1.2; 3; 5; P1;P2;P3;P4;P5;
    define a curve formed of 50 edges, of lengths
    following a geometrical ratio 1.2 and passing by the 5 points,
    of components piecewise polynomials of degree 3
    Attention: 
    To obtain the interpolation points as vertices of the mesh
    choose a ratio=1 and an edge number = k (number of points-1)
         
12: OPENED B-SPLINE FROM CONTROL POINTS
    The curve is of same type as the previous 11, but the points
     are not interpolation points, but control points.
    Execpted the extremities, the control points are NOT on the curve
    Example: LINE12; I; 12;
             45; 1; 2; 5; P1;P2;P3;P4;P5;
    define a curve formed of 45 edges, of constant lengths,
    of components piecewise polynomials of degree 2
    de tailles constantes, polynomiale par morceaux de
    passing by P1 and P5 only, and 
    tangent at P1 to P1-P2 and P4-P5 at P5.

21: CLOSED B-SPLINE FROM INTERPOLATION POINTS
22: CLOSED B-SPLINE FROM CONTROL POINTS
    Same types of lines as options 11; 12; with the difference that
    Example: LINE21; I; 21; 50; 1; 3; 8;  P1;P2;P3;P4;P5;P6;P7;P8; 
  { vertices P2 P4 P6 P8 et middles of a square P1 P3 P5 P7 }
    define a closed curve formed of 50 edges, with components
    piecewise polynomials of degree 3 and passing by the 8 points.
    The 9th point is implicitly P1.

24: INTERSECTION OF PLANE-TRUNCATED CONE
    the plane is defined by 3 points.
    the troncated cone is defined by 2 points on its axis,
    the radius of circle of the section in the orthogonal plane
    to the axis at each of these 2 points
    Remark: a TRONCATED CONE becomes a CYLINDRE if the 2 radii are equals
    Attention: These 2 planes delimit also some edges of the intersection
    and the line may be opened or closed, composed of one or many pieces.

25: INTERSECTION OF PLANE-ELLIPSOID
    the plane is defined by 3 points.
    The ellipsoid is defined by its centre and
    the 3 points located at the half axis extremities
    Of course, the reference system defined by these points
    must be DIRECT!

26: INTERSECTION OF 2 TRUNCATED CONES
    the troncated cone is defined by 2 points on its axis,
    the radius of circle of the section in the orthogonal plane
    to the axis at each of these 2 points
    Remark: a TRONCATED CONE becomes a CYLINDRE if the 2 radii are equals
    Attention: These 2 planes delimit also some edges of the intersection
    and the line may be opened or closed, composed of one or many pieces.

27: INTERSECTION OF 2 CYLINDERS ONE WITH Z-AXIS & THE SECOND
    with X or Y-axis centred at the ORIGIN of axes.
    the Z-axis cylinder must have the smallest radius.
    the line intersection is defined by
    - an angular sector of longitude TETA0 and TETA1
    - its Z cote Z positive or negative. 
    Example: INTERSECTION; I; 27; 15; 2; 10; 5; -90; 90; -1;
    line intersection of 2 cylinders of Z-axis of radius 5
    and Y-axis of radius 10, formed of 15 edges from the
    longitude (angle with x in the plan XY) -90 degrees (-Y)
    and 90 degrees (+Y) for negative to choose the inferior
    intersection line

28: FILLET LINE WITH A TANGENT CIRCLE
    It is a segment, followed by a tangent arc of circle,
    followed by a new tangent segment.
    The fillet is defined by 3 points P1 P2 P3 cf figure

                P1--------------- .      * P2      
                                     .     
                                       .   
                                        . 
                                        |
                                        |  
                                        |
                                        P3
    Example: L28; I; 28; 33; 1; {radius of the arc of circle} 
             P1;P2;P3;
    define a line from P1, formed of 33 edges,
    tangent at an arc of circle of radius 1 to the segment P1-P2,
    and tangent to the segment P2-P3.
    the point P2 is NOT on the line. 

35: EXTRACTED EDGES OF A LINE BY EDGE NUMBERS
    Every edge of number between the first and second input number
    is an edge of the extracted line 
    Example: L35; I; 35; INITIAL_LINE; 5; 15;
    extract the edges 5 to 15 of INITIAL_LINE.

36: EXTRACTED EDGES OF A LINE BY A CRITERION
    Every edge of the 3 coordinates of its 2 vertices which
    returns true for the criterion, is an edge of the extracted line 
    Example: L36; I; 36; INITIAL_LINE;
             deffunc PLANE_X_POSITIVE(x,y,z);
               PLANE_X_POSITIVE = (x>=0);
             endfunc;
             PLANE_X_POSITIVE;
    extract the edges with vertices of x>=0.

37: INTERNAL OR BOUNDARY EDGES OF A SURFACE
    Every edge of FE of a surface and such that the 3 coordinates
    of its 2 vertices returns true for the criterion,
    is an edge of the extracted line 
    Example: L37; I; 37; SURFACE_EXISTANTE;
             deffunc SQUARE_POSITIVE(x,y,z);
             SQUARE_POSITIVE = (x>=0) et (y>=0); endfunc;
             SQUARE_POSITIVE; 3;
    extract the surface FE edges of which 2 vertices have
    a X and y>=0.
    The last input integer say what type of edge must be extracted
    1 : only boundary edges (belong to 1 and only 1 FE)
    2 : only internal edges (belong to 2 FE)
    3 : boundary and internal edges

40: RESTRUCTURATION OF AN UNSTRUCTURED LINE
    simply connex, if it is possible, to reduce the storage
    Example: L40_STRUCTURED; I; 40; LINE_UNSTRUCTURED; 
    If the line LINE_UNSTRUCTURED was already STRUCTURED,
    then L40_STRUCTURED is not created.
  
43: INVERSE THE VERTICES OF A STRUCTURED LINE
    The vertices 1 to NB of the structured line are
    ordering from NB to 1.
    This option is used to change the normal vector of this line.

48: IMPOSED POINTS ONTO the NEAREST VERTEX of the LINE
    The 3 coordinates of the nearest vertex to a named point
    are replaced by the 3 coordinates of the point.
    Attention, the quality of finite elements may be modified.

50: MAPPING OF AN ACTUAL LINE
    An existing LINE is transformed by a predefined MAPPING
    Example: L50; LINE_SYMMETRY; 50; INITIAL_LINE;
    The vertices of the LINE L50 are the images
    of vertices of the INITIAL_LINE by the mapping LINE_SYMMETRY

51: UNION OF SEVERAL LINES
    The line will be an UNION of LINES grouped under
    a same name.
    The common vertices of 2 lines are identified
    to form an unique vertex. If this identification is NOT
    correct, modify the identification precision of vertices
    by the option 20; of Debut menu.
    An UNION of lines is handled after as any other line
    Example: L51; I; 51; 5; L1;L2;L3;L4;L5;

81: RENAME THE LINE
    ATTENTION TO THE ORDER OF INPUT!
    Example: NEW_NAME; I; 81; OLD_NAME;
    Rename the line OLD_NAME into NEW_NAME

82: DELETE THE LINE
    Delete the line from the input of its name done previously
    Example: L82; I; 82;   delete the line L82 if it existed
